    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-21T10:16:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-21T10:16:00-05:00" n="582"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d582">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 862.20235/208</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SFJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-21T11:00:00-04:16">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 21, 1917, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 3.50 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Luxburg telegrams, 57 in number,<note n="2" xml:id="d582fn2">In addition to
                        the three originally published by the American Government; these had been
                        sent by the Argentine Government to Washington for decoding and were also
                        published there. See the Ambassador’s telegram of Sept. 21, 11 a.m., and the
                        Acting Secretary’s telegram of Oct. 27, 7 p.m., <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_329">pp. 329</ref>, <ref target="#pg_353"
                        >353</ref>.</note> were given to the evening papers yesterday with a
                    statement from the Foreign Office that they <pb facs="0565" n="393"
                        xml:id="pg_393"/> Were All that had been received from Washington, except
                    the three referred to in my December 15, 6 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d582fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> The <hi rend="italic">communiqué</hi> goes on to say that
                    the telegrams make a series of misstatements too astounding to be qualified, as
                    they are entirely contrary to the terms in which the negotiations were
                    maintained and decided. “Equally absurd are the suppositions which attribute to
                    the Argentine Government attitudes with respect to other nations—the Argentine
                    Government therefore disavows totally the contents of these telegrams in all
                    that relates to their opinion and proceedings.”</p>
                <p>None of the leading newspapers make editorial comment as yet except <hi
                        rend="italic">La Nación</hi>, which asks where the rest of the 400 telegrams
                    are that the Argentine Government said it possessed.</p>
                <p>The telegrams were not referred to in the debate in Congress last night. The
                    general opinion is that the most important telegrams were the four [<hi
                        rend="italic">three?</hi>] already published.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SFJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
